//             ----- Introduction -----
// This is an example Scene.

// Any text placed after a "//" is a comment that will be ignored when loading this file.
// Whitespace in the definition of a Scene will be ignored when loading this file.

//             ----- Understanding the Scene -----
// A Scene is a 3D-space in which Composite Mesh Objects (CMOs) and Lights exist and are used.
// You define your CMOs and Lights in seperate files, then simply declare which lights and
// CMOs you want in the scene and their positions, as shown below.

//             ----- Defining the Scene -----
// The Scene gets its name from the filename, meaning this Scene is called "example".


// Each attribute must be in the formats laid out below, 
// each ended with a comma if any attribute comes after.
// The exception being the ending brackets not needing a comma after.

// Each light is enclosed in brackets
// 4 lights max, any additional will be ignored.
{
    // Here you will enter the name of the light, in this case: "example".
    light: (example),

    // Here you will enter the position of the chosen light.
    //        (  X,   Y,   Z) | Using a max of 4 decimal spaces (ex. 0.0000)
    position: (0.0, 2.0, 4.0)
}
{
    light: (example),
    position: (-4.0, 2.0, 4.0)
}
{
    light: (example),
    position: (4.0, 2.0, 4.0)
}
{
    // At a minimum you must assign a light.
    // The position will be zero'd out by default if omitted.
    light: (example),
    position: (0.0, 6.0, -6.0)
}

// Each CMO is enclosed in brackets
{
    // Here you will enter the name of the CMO, in this case: "example".
    CMO: (example),

    // Here you will enter the position of the chosen CMO.
    //        (  X,   Y,   Z) | Using a max of 4 decimal spaces (ex. 0.0000)
    position: (0.0, 0.0, 0.0)
}

// As shown above, you can reuse the same lights and CMOs repeatedly. Each one will considered seperate.